The Menu of an Obese Child: It Doesn't Eat Breakfast and Eat Sausage for Dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown - obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important it is for the healthy development of a person the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had fries at dinner on the eve of the education campaign under the motto "obesity is no coincidence".
In families with fatties, exercise is not exactly one of the favorite activities, but it also affects the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent responded that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools throughout the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was the second year of the "Obesity is not a coincidence" campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever Society.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the terribly increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed, for example, indicated eating breakfast five times a day in the breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper-evening-bread mode—one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” one of the survey results says.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative trifles, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the pupils’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
The worst was the finding that in every tenth family, breakfast is not eaten at all.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test showed, among other things, that in the families of overweight children, unhealthy french fries are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70%)
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do - namely, only 15 percent.
Build your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to assemble their own meal plan according to appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and of course sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, the main dish, pasta was just ahead of poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey respondents who completed the questionnaire after completing the clarifying lecture "Obesity is not a coincidence" there was a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition in many cases," is stated in the results of the project.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limes, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed into the questionnaire much more often poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
