V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The original carefree ride is turned into a routine trip to the early shift by a series of completely avoidable, dilettantic mistakes.
It was possible to fulfil the ambitions to a large extent, but what good is that if obviously nobody wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the counters, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already aged game series "Need for Speed" to a new dimension again and in the playable demonstration examples, he actually appeared to be not only one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the fit-in passages in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to at NFS, in the end, a lot is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they are quite decent arcade races, but overall, the game is shrunk by some superfluous flaws that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time in history, the main character Jack has some personal problems; the only solution seems to be to take part in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole range of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don’t have the impression for a moment that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing world-shaking.
But the drive through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape looks visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, atypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts visibility.
In the mountains, you have to be very careful not to get spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are built quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And then there's the police, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It’s more about some interactive animations in which Jack runs away from anyone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (in concrete terms, only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage of the thing, because this element has at least no chance of becoming boring - it is in the context of the above said one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model progresses in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, although it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, one could not say that it is bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model will continue to do quite well for an action-packed race, even though you could find better ones in the competition.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems only arise after a certain time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not entirely OK.
It is hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how the car behaves before any impact on any object, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: In narrow overtaking or passing by oncoming cars, you "strip" the other cars only slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations, you get to spin and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the carriage is going to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter, it's always annoying.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last point of the track.
Only - in every race you have only five restarts.
When you have exhausted them, everything starts from the beginning.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't work, but you shouldn't rely on it.
But sometimes the restart doesn’t even help, so nothing helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
Quite uncomfortable is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, you have to go through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don’t fit through.
Elsewhere, you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent passing by in front of two cars, but until you arrive there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to turn them around or brake them.
And it does not matter when you arrive there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The opponents have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken at the same place by the same opponent and here again without regard to the time.
The most insane is at the end of the game on the long bridge that you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to overtake one here on devil come out.
And if he is in front of you, then of course he takes the view away from you, so that you drive your own car in Klump a few times at first.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses the pleasure of the game.
And that is a pity, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is overall quite entertaining and in some places so full of action that you almost no longer know where your head stands.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what's "guilty" about it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the car change during the course of the races.
You should not miss the petrol stations on the route, because here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight motorways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
The task mode (challenges) also goes hand in hand with the mode of the game history - i.e. the races in the individual locations that you know from the history.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points to win for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
To get to the higher driver level, different items must be opened up: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is simultaneously connected with the online function Autolog, which compares, among other things, the own achieved results with those of other players and also ensures further collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race in history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (mean roads), where you race on the rails in the dark for a long time (mean roads).
On the speedometer, numbers can see between 150 and 200 km/h (meanway), but there suddenly comes a subway from behind and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial office, we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this concerns in particular the accidents with a greater number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use to you anyway.
The sound is ok and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a broader scale than possible to younger audiences, a soundtrack was created a lá "something from everyone" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
Need for Speed: The Run is the best of Need for Speed: The Run.
If the game had not been compromised by the aforementioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we would have been able to maintain with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game looks kind of unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared for these mistakes to get in your eyes with the power of airport headlights.
