Brand Story:
IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to look for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM’s strategy, that would probably be the word “longevity”.
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since its inception.
The foundation for this longevity was already laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Even he used the slogan that countless global problems could be solved easily if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the trademark around which the life of the future giant was to take place (and at the same time the title of the company's in-house magazine, which began to be published at IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen’s thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and succeeded for a century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society over the course of our first century.
We hope we can do even more in the next hundred years,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, today’s director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Well-thought-out system
As early as the 1930s, Watson provided social care to his employees – in the same way as the entrepreneur Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in Czechoslovakia: The IBM people were one of the first American employees to have paid leave, insurance from the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes and a well-thought-out remuneration system for the best innovators and traders.
IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
From the very beginning, the company was ingenious in talent promotion - as one of the first companies in the world to eliminate any discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan that Palmisan will be replaced by a woman next year at the head of IBM is also - by Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, until now she has held the position of Sales, Marketing and Strategy Chief.
IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings in recent years, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Her unwavering position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
“From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company,” said Economist, Harvard Business School professor and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology," George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research added.
As the company itself emphasizes, it is a difference to only be present in the market or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM - known in the states as "Big Blue" because of its family logo, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in an incredible product range - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM holds the most patents and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His best-known inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swap, barcode or even the floppy disk.
With approximately $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM was the second largest technology company this year (after Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unfortunate were, for example, the experiment with the own OS/2 operating system, the online service Prodigy or the computer IBM PC jr.
“Business is based on moving forward, so you shouldn’t be emotionally attached to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms – and if they don’t work, leaving them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
IBM’s profits are largely driven by services, software and hardware, with one-fifth of them each.
In 1990, hardware was still the most represented with a share of more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-profit assets, while at the same time investing $58 billion in the purchase of future-oriented technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased its investment volume in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives today’s crisis harmlessly.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120% since 2008 and the company’s net profit is growing continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is: Everything can be changed, but not the values.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also overcome the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutters to Space Flights
Founded in New York a hundred years ago, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name – Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was not until 1924 that she adopted the name IBM – originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
IBM was founded by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous stitch card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the boss of the competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then eclipsed IBM’s founders – based on Watson’s ideas, the company’s invincible culture and identity continues to this day.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began producing and distributing all kinds of machines for trading - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four decades Watson led the company, he doubled its revenue to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped guide NASA's flights to space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous man's flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of that time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off in the last three years is the concept of a smarter planet.
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a smart way in areas not even planned so far, e.g. also to improve the situation in traffic and in city administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which is designed to help merchants lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a branch in the then Czechoslovakia – the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe Headquarters is located in Prague, where a world-class research team is also present, dealing with voice recognition technology.
