Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state-approved travel agencies in the former <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the travel agencies mainly sold trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West only the elect were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Lake Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was also allowed, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or sleep in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, things hadn’t gone well.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and datches - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvety revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A tremendous paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday destination of the Czechs - Croatia at all until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation to the neighboring Western European countries was lifted, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park while traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money to stay in a hotel or in a guesthouse at the time.
A typical feature of Czechs travelling abroad was a luggage compartment packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech krona - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our level of living and thus the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare travel by charter flights after 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had currency-free payments with all the advanced countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was completed - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly to distant sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are served directly from the Czech Republic.
About 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita for a single holiday, including the cost at the resort.
