21st house in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won awards in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and decayed.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
When swarmed with modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer is a fitting and famous example for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition.
Schwanzer's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built a pavilion at the next World Exhibition in Austria.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like outbuilding in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna's Südbahnhof, rebuilt and a museum of the 20th century opened in 1962 - the "20th House" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has come down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a fortune in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has succeeded.
Husslein-Arco, a doctoral art historian with a considerable career, among other things in her youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, emphatically carried out the conversion with politicians and monument conservationists, she raised public funds and private sponsorship funds and set the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the execution then Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he sensibly rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him a "immensely important place" where he had seen the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which was already lost in generosity and ease when it was transferred to Vienna and reused.
During the current renovation, there were far greater problems: the building was "an energy hurl," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was inserted and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light trench between house and road ensures exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house has been painted in the old red-brown anti-rust shade.
And the cinema is still exactly as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found, which is good and cheap and also liked the Heritage Office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and light.
“It was difficult with the pavilion coming from Brussels,” Krischanitz recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city story.”
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because there has been an urban development luck: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "main station quarter", with office and residential buildings, is being created.
And another lucky event may still happen: the 21st house could get reinforcements from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle, and it is heard that she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbouring location in the Swiss garden.
