Nothing, it seems, is spared the once so proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of the silent and solid, but also sophisticated, Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she wanted to become a huge number in investment banking.
In 2007, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, as an investment bank, it had advanced into the league of the world’s largest banks.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later longtime banking professor in Zurich, Hans Geiger, tells us: "I always used UBS as a model of a good bank for my students at the time."
"From today's point of view, one wonders: how could I be so wrong?"
He was greatly mistaken.
In 2007, it was revealed for the first time that something went wrong in UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli resigned surprisingly, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker.
A few months later, he knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment division had been fooled by subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase of CHF 13 billion.
For this, she actually found investors, but ones that some would have been whining about until recently: an opaque Asian sovereignty fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereignty fund that was so hidden that they didn’t even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
It got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new billions in losses, Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel, Switzerland’s second best-paid Board of Directors, resigned in 2006.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: UBS faced a collapse in view of its misinvestment in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought the UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion Swiss francs for a compulsory convertible bond, through which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to be home to such large banks.
After all, UBS’ balance sheet total in 2007 was more than five times that of Switzerland’s economic output (see graph).
"Once again, we could not save the UBS," says banking researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
A few months later, UBS surrendered in the tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have evaded taxes with the help of the bank.
She also agreed to pay $780 million as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty surcharge.
In this way, UBS more or less openly acknowledged that it had helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer funds.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both key business areas: investment banking through misspelling and asset management through tax evasion aid.
And just when things got a little quieter again, just when you thought that UBS was going to make it again, this unfortunate dealer story follows: a single dealer lost 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it turns out: with the risk management in investment banking, it obviously still does not work.
"With the Adoboli case, it has been found that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and professor of finance at the banking institute at the University of Zurich.
The Chief Financial Officer of a large German bank is also sure: "The problem with UBS is that it has no control over risk control."
It was precisely the idea of the caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago started to become guardians of the world’s great fortunes: no too great risks, but security for money – even beyond the Alpine Republic, the world might collapse.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unshakable reliability like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The head office of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the strong Swiss private bank - it is only a little bigger.
Already the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich’s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the central station to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rentals are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellers such as Tiffany’s can be found here among Swiss traditional shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have been residing here for centuries: from the National Bank to the palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
You enter the reception hall of UBS through a heavy swinging door.
Inside, the walls are covered in marble, in front of it are thick leather armchairs, next to the bank logo a large sign for the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has both Swiss large banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but eventually displaced - or betrayed, as the boss of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two major banks.
UBS has become far too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons had also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, gave it first high profits and then the debacle: No European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven-million country decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS crash."
Up to 68 billion francs, or around 45 billion euros, were granted by the politicians to save the bankrupt big bank.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly in the size of the UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged into a massive group.
A bank emerged, which was already too big for the small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and continued to grow.
The two different UBS precursor banks helped to complement each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer, but already more internationalized bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers got a lot of money cheaply, with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the highly intellectual, humble, who understands a lot of models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man who has worked himself up from banking to the very top."
But in the end, Ospel relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," Geiger says.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, perhaps.
Obviously, overconfidence came before the case.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings, at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: Goldman Sachs to fall from the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
That's where UBS wanted to go, to the top.
Some steps had already been taken.
In the foreign exchange business and in stock trading, she played at the top.
Business consultants who were commissioned, however, highlighted a weakness: In the international interest rate business, in the banker's language "fixed income", there is a huge distance from the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime assets.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and passed securities on American mortgage loans - but also kept risks itself.
Even when other banks long ago sought to exit.
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there," says banking expert Geiger.
So great is the euphoria, so deep is the case.
One manager after the other had to leave as the attempts to clean up were more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS have become a centrifugal seat and are unstable to this day.
Anyone who runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He must find a strategy for a bank that has lost all obvious business models.
Bank researcher Geiger already has an idea: stop investment banking, focus on asset management, return to the Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking should shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new banking director Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has prevailed: he should permanently run the business of UBS, the Zurich bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to the mid-nineties level.
He cut 3,500 jobs.
But that won't be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does she want to make money with?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is probably asking himself right now.
So far, he has only said publicly that he and his wife will first look for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
