Intelligent crows spread in cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: Crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities residents complain about dirt and noise of the animals.
A cure for the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer available from the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian empty.
There, experts from the entire federal territory consulted on possible solutions.
You are looking for alternatives in cities
Nature conservationists attributed the problems in cities to the rural exodus of the particularly protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture increasingly destroys traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the falling of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs exist in Westphalian Soest, in the northwest, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the district caused negative headlines.
Critics had described catching the animals in bird traps and killing them with clubs as particularly brutal.
"The normal displacement, the engraving, does nothing," the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer noted.
Nests splashing away with water or falling trees often have undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals evade, large colonies split up and spread out elsewhere."
Extinction is only conceivable as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surrounding area, the problem in the cities could not be solved, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable a combination of enraging the animals from sensitive living areas and lure offers to resettle them in other places.
The psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens, on the other hand, advocated a completely different way of dealing with the animals: "A pimple in the face can ultimately best be tolerated confidently."
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberg Crow Teaching Path in Schleswig-Holstein, where signs inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project has already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on criticism of the noise of the birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but even make their own tools as a tool.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of birds reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to bring down a scaffold with stones in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they determinedly realized what size and shape a stone must have in order to collapse the platform.
In a second attempt, the clever crows had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had placed wire pieces on them.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even succeeded in doing so at once.
