Facebook’s hiding personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — just like marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with Adds, but instead of linking up with a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking about their level of education, their attitudes toward violence, and their own assessment of their future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their offices once.
"It's a fairly new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and annoyed about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising distortion, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens."
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as in "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with that page’s name in the title by nearly 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this site you can study people you don’t normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have allowed them access,” Bartlett says.
“With Facebook, it all falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say the site provides a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full rush on Facebook were significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who remained silent on this topic.
Moreno suggests that equivalent students, such as housing consultants, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t recognized it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Morenos’ co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook is also constantly collecting data from its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to – Masters of Digital Freedom have long known that the site should make their large data pit accessible to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. In order to be able to play scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, they allow the site to share their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined students’ public pages on Facebook.
"As for her, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant will be absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research has to take care of the social – and lots of social life is still taking place offline.”
