7 Lessons from the Interview with Deceased Steve Jobs Showed at a Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted this week before special film screenings in the major markets, is how much this creative head understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who zealously crafted charts — a man who believed that many executives suffer from “a disease of thinking,” that “a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Idiots" about the break-up of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs, in which they had one of the rare, in-depth conversations.
At that time, more than 10 years had passed since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple. And he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringley's interview was used in specialist idiots, he says the copy templates of the interview were missing on delivery.
Only after Jobs' death was a complete VHS copy discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly revised film footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which will be coming to the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to hate extensive interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
Over the course of the interview, there are four longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and pushes him to respond more quickly to topics or incidents of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, the Lost Interview seems somehow eeriely far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right or wrong in his opinion and represents his own vision of the computer’s future.
It’s one thing to read posthumous appreciations of Jobs’ career, but seeing Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the way to greatness is something quite different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he went off and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, 'Why do you do things?'. And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's made easy.'
No one knows why he does what he does. No one in the business really thinks deeply about things.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astonished at how costs were recorded—usually starting with “standard costs” that were quantified by mere assumption and then adjusted by “deviation”—he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
How the Pope was ridiculed:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that could sneak into the telephone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs’ enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a paid phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent stuff half a dozen times around the globe and when you screamed into the phone, it came out a minute later in the phone next door,” Jobs says, smiling.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We both, we didn’t know much, but we could build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs continues to tell of a glorious prank that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called at the Vatican in the middle of the night via Blue Box and wanted to talk to the Pope while imitating Henry Kissinger as well as they could.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself got on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unpreparedly called Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of HP’s employees visiting the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was as tall as a suitcase, had a small screen with Braun's tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for her.
How to Improve Innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he built some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment deadline of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later on at Apple, he remembers the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember punchy arguments... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for $15, which was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are declining:
Long before resurrecting Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you're making a better copyer or printer, okay?"
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [are those people] who ultimately lead the businesses and the product that pushes people out of decision making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is eradicated by the people who have no concept regarding good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
This happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been 10 times bigger if it had been Microsoft in the 1990s.
They got the defeat from victory.
About innovation as an art form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop that great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about your subtleties.
You have to make votings, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5,000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best things humans have created and then trying to bring those things together into what you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it had not been the computer industry, they would have created fantastic things in other areas.
