How to Reveal a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy managing the allegations of sexual harassment by several women, both sides accusing each other of lying.
Penn State’s leadership is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports of a retired football coach sexually abusing boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nicolas Sarkozy claimed to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign funding violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating in school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they were doing well even in their performance exams.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
However, many of these lies are regarded as emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "discovering lies" is one that is important for everyone to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a societal game such as charades, in which the goal is to shout “Have yourself!”, unmasking a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data gathered over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most ancient myths about lying have been uncovered.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don’t always stutter, stammer, blush, and babble.
However, it is not possible to conclude from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and unmask.
A skilled liar can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, questioning and timing.
I’ve spent several years exploring the scientific findings of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of disguise, and it’s clear that disguising a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us navigate in our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or administering belongs to one’s own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at evaluating other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people are more likely to lie than introverted people, that men are more likely to lie "self-oriented" than women, whose lies are more "oriented toward others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly lies).
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of having lied to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First of all, observe this person’s normal behavior.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a point of reference for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone is usually constantly tripping with the foot so that they don’t wrongly accuse him if he trips with the foot during a meeting.
Then watch for accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells that shriek, not as evidence of a disguise.
