Climate change has slowed the economy
In the first year that Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and unemployment increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and sparked great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of the climatic adversity, growth cannot be spoken of, but on the contrary the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrowed the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which slowed down further economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the impact of frost, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed, mainly vegetable, maize and chickpea crops.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, because from January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent, from 969 percent to 5.28 percent in July.
Lower liquidity
According to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including losses of liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts in funds by Congress' anti-money laundering legislation, because for those who illegally accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, on the one hand because of the problems of entry and on the other because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Black Labour
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if you take into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of the workforce in the country that works without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and unemployment are the lowest wages in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, which is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and growing unemployment, the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last decade has been recorded in 2011. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI from January to June was $ 630 597, which corresponds to a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the $ 5 143 312 in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaria de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno, for its part, recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from tertiary companies.
The debts
Given the economic crisis, the state government applied for a loan of 3,000,000 pesos to the National Congress in July to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The state congress approved an amount of 200,600,000 pesos, but by November no positive effects of the debt could be found on any of the economic sectors in the country.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé’s inability to govern obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (Mexico State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry), stated that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa has been really poor this year, hard work has to be done to recover the terrain lost this year, and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López commented that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made economic development of the country difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important consequences is a slowed economy that is not moving enough to produce economic dynamics that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining the Appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, stated that the state must be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that guides the government’s efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress in the government.
"There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively, and what I can say is that the government has been working and is aware that there is a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
