The Court Approves the Transition to Digital Television in Mexico for 2015
The conversion of analogue to digital signals is one of the most important changes in recent years worldwide.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Presidential Decree, and under which the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be forwarded, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Legislative Decree detailing the switch to terrestrial digital television.
By this decision, the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate was rejected because it did not receive the necessary qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality.
In the project for the lawsuit drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed that the legislative decree be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations relating to radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel).
In favor of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. After accepting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero stopped applying the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities to establish the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project, which was also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister expressed disagreement with the project’s arguments, in the sense that the state government cannot regulate the measures that the public administration is supposed to take by means of general rules.
"I also don't think that doing so would impair the independence of the regulator," she also recalled that for the planning of strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, the central government is responsible for managing state affairs.
Replacing analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality, and more channels.
The postponement of the change, she said, was a postponement of the benefit of digitization, which is a decision in the public interest, which has not only technical aspects, "because it covers economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "made the action of the entire system necessary, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a set of features that the Constitution placed in the hands of the central government."
It recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital transition, through the government, despite having highly specialized facilities.
“It cannot be concluded that the government will intervene in the powers of Congress by issuing the contested legislative decree, because the laws passed by the legislature will be complied with,” she assured.
