It should be remembered that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, electoral law or electoral justice law to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they did not come into force during this election. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Gazette within the deadlines provided for it, arguing that he had no objections to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional action filed by the local legislature and judged the state commissioner's vote on constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful" since he does not have the right to "decide or veto it."
