On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
They read an excerpt from the conversation, whose full copy can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica for a holiday, it’s such a beautiful country that we’re sure to stay there for a few more days.
It is exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted and they are experiencing the days before the concert most intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put a little pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years took place in the last two weeks.
We played at a few giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and we love the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua for surfing. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we learned about people who love surfing.
With a view of the tour you have offered giant shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there before, we also set no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
- Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and each one likes a different song, so it’s not easy to decide which one we’re going to play.
If we add two or three songs that we haven’t played for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they might fall into oblivion.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I believe, therefore also for the audience.
With this tour, you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, which sounds like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are enthusiastic about producing music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to participate actively in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Occasionally a band emerges from a city, but it is unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We’re still excited to be friends with them all and we’re honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual for a band like yours to stay together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive and, moreover, we care about each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship to fame has not always been easy, but thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it’s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds that love your music.
As long as you remember that people came because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought to life without being obsessed with being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about other things and about music and football.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that’s why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band best. So we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. This will be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
So many+
The first ones I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it’s no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they’re still important today, I think that’s great because it’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
- Why?
That's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little lighthearted, but there are other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
Both of them tears came to me when I heard Ed playing them. They're very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life – for example, when you lose a family member or a friend – that affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody it for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
