Fujimori returned to hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor informed.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, Congressman and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori was being examined for three days at the Peruvian Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas Hospital to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not wish to do so because he thought he was innocent.
He was operated on four times on tongue cancer and lost 18 kilos of weight, along with other conditions such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in the Detention Centre of the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la Policía since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly operating during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and entrepreneurs will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues of the region
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday, which, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the highlight of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica seeks support from Calderón regarding the French incident when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community. This statement was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has presided over the G20 since November, a group consisting of the most powerful emerging and industrialized countries in the world. Since January of this year, a tax information exchange agreement has been in place to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the concretization of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "gray list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not implemented all international standards for tax cooperation.
At the business level, a free trade agreement has been in place between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
