Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organization was created to prevent the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the Trinijove social welfare organization have led to important results: In this quarter of a century, 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are more than 100 jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, a balance sheet was drawn yesterday at an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people participated.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems at risk of marginality.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by many leaders of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association in these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives from different directions during election campaign times proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
Apart from the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol participated in the celebrations of the former socialist education minister Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and current left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of the Savings Bank La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was created in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far is "a good foundation".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new to the club and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on the street Balmes 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without resisting.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of House No. 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people left yesterday at noon voluntarily the building they had illegally occupied and where they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighbourhood to despair. The eviction took place on a judicial order without any police intervention.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the property manager confirmed.
The squatters, who had occupied 11 of the building's 13 apartments - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, painted the walls and left all kinds of trash, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
On the three lower floors, huge parties lasting up to two days were celebrated, driving the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the start of the occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters were making their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the leisure venue had been accused by the neighbors of disturbance to the rest, while according to her statement, the noise was not from the visitors of the disco, but from the house occupiers and especially from the guests of the festivals that were organized there, which, according to the angry neighbors, have become more and more long in recent weeks.
The manager of the discotheque explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana also confirmed that it had received more complaints from its neighbors in recent weeks.
The leader of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the city council of Barcelona, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had asked last week to clear the building without delay and to tackle the problems of bourgeois coexistence and the downfall of the neighborhood.
He explained that only one floor of the building had been occupied before the summer, but that the squatters had penetrated into all floors of the building and almost all apartments in recent months. In some cases, there had even been theft.
In that sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to take action against the anti-social acts in the building."
