Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed Secretary of Government Francisco Blake and seven other people.
The Secretaria de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the findings of the investigation into the accident in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people were killed indicate that the helicopter with its entire intact structure had collided directly against the ground without the pilot having been able to conduct an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, said the pilot had confirmed before launch that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing was in contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing the hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the prerequisites for transporting the personnel.
In addition, he said that no helicopter parts were found in the investigations in the area where the aircraft had crashed.
"No aircraft parts were found elsewhere during the search, the surcharge affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
Currently, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but it can take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at cruise speed and the plane fell on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visible flight:
In accordance with the flight norms, it was a flight according to the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions during the take-off and during the flight onwards towards the border area between Mexico City and Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds rose.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact spot:
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the helicopter match. There may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or deviation from the flight route prior to the impact.
Spreading the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter had impacted from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter, with its intact structure, had collided with the ground.
No signs of fire or explosion:
The remains of the plane at the scene of the accident do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest findings indicate several ground contacts.
On-site investigations found aircraft parts at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, with slopes of 7 to 30 degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area beyond the locked area at the crash site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, intensifying the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had collided with the ground.
MSS Announces a Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
She leads a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by specialists of the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence" to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI Clinic, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate program at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports grounds of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (west of the state of México) and will continue since October 8 at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will continue on the sports field of Independencia (south of the capital district) and be completed on that of Morelos (north of the capital district).
He explained that the goal of the study is to get to know the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he stated that the aim is for three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 to complete nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history of disease to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He further explained that on the aforementioned Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be conducted on the occasion of health care staff concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent, and obesity increased dramatically," the IMSS specialist stressed.
He stated that the search for genetic markers is justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico is different from that of other peoples.
He stated that on average, a (e) Mexican (in) is 65 percent of Native American, 30 percent of European and 5 percent of African descent, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of energy (calories) consumed by us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the study participants would be a comprehensive study of the children, in which it would be determined whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even examine the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the pre-stage.
