Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were paid to the signs emerging from the road pavement, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes when the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM.
In his lecture "Technical Impact Holes", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low one - the so-called malthene. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic toughness behavior.
Toughly elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very viscous and almost solid at 50° C., while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ’s researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible road surfaces composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, it requires a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
The one that receives and distributes the most forces from this road surface also requires the supporting layer to have an appropriate thickness and the material it is made of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the wear layer's behavior.
When the terrain becomes moist, water enters the layer and is difficult to exit, causing a softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is created," he said, "the outer layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of potholes, so the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and that this regulation must be complied with to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are even already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes can be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
