So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopicist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4th, a lophoscopicist from the Cali Prosecutor’s Unit (CTI) came in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Forzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia – Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces): “Alfonso Cano” by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopicists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, was on standby.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he often had to spend five days in the jungle to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the deployment against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big awaited him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was supposed to identify two bodies and that one was suspected to be the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was supposed to take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was with the investigator, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, because this was not in the slightest similar to the pictures he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer of the area, was not wearing glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body’s fingerprints to those on the print sheet.
He had seen it right: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this Puerto Tejada man was in charge of informing the Defense Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
In search of traces
For a dactyloscope from the Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in resolving a crime.
Lophoscopics not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery cases and confirm the identity of the detained persons.
At their arrest, many offenders present false ID documents or they have none.
We take their fingerprints and search for them in the database.
The researcher told us that in the event of a theft, he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand at this very point when he pulled out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprint picking, but in this case we were able to take the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or charged.
Recently, a dead person was found surrounded by bottles of liquor.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member could be suspicious, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that the murderer is involved, he is still associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopyist explained that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents were taken from the object."
When they appear, a planting cell or tape is used for taking away.
Afterwards, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Register of Persons.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity documents," explained the expert from the CTI.
He said that not everything was as it would be in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you carry out a corresponding comparison.
