But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
From the right side was the tone of Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", from the left side by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "cannot absorb the entire poverty of the world".
The only difference is in the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left in 2005.
From both camps, immigrants were perceived as a burden to the economy and French society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit to the immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande is confined to banalities that point out that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may potentially impact the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economics experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among the specialists regarding the positive impact of immigration on economic growth, immigration and immigration rates.
Restricting immigration would weaken growth and damage the labour market situation.
Fears about the influence of migrants are based on the notion that they threaten to substitute the domestic workforce, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage workers, since they focus on occupations in sectors that are unloaded in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that attract local wage workers little, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with job offer.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect of immigration on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants will result in a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
