Europe has invented democracy, now remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a delicate asset.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had allowed the whole 20th century to pass over the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Colonel in Greece.
Some may have thought it was enough to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy prevail over its enemies once and for all.
It has been known since Napoleon "the little one" that it was a feature of the mental attitude.
The universal right to vote, which is the necessary condition of democracy, is not sufficient for this and can just as well become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social community spirit, a jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe, in which we find ourselves, is an economic crisis, but it is just as much, and first and foremost, a political and democratic crisis.
The change of attitude of the Greek true-false referendum would have had a double enlightening character in this respect: on the one hand, the need for a powerful return of politics, and on the other, the worrying feeling of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and that the Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to win to push for the success of the national referendum, which was organised depending on the necessities and in the wrong order.
A free ticket for the European sole ruler or a leap with closed eyes into the void of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want Hackebeil, but a collective task, out of full law, clarified and steady, an election and democracy, this time on a European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - you no longer know where to end the list - since there is only one crisis, and it prevails in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that submits to the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated at the international level.
One is concerned about transfers of sovereignty towards Europe - but it is all Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it every one of its affiliated nations.
The urgency is to return the leadership of the European project to the People's Sovereignty.
It is up to the whole to see if Europeans can reduce the burden of their debt, free themselves from the markets and start a future by investing.
The exit from the crisis is conditional on European-level decisions that cannot be made without total democratic legitimacy without certainly leading us to ruin.
After this proposal has long been opposed by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, today everyone urges European economic governance to do so.
All right.
But to imagine this without political integration and a stronger democracy - as it is intended for the citizens - would be another foolishness and another dead end.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
In order to create the Republic in France, it was necessary to "create" Republicans.
The revolution of the interests alone could not do enough here.
This instruction remains valid.
We must build a better integrated Europe at economic level.
This can only be achieved by creating a more politically democratic Europe, a truly European popular sovereignty.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
"Contactless" smart cards become a common good
The world trade fair for smart cards will open its doors in Villepinte near Paris on Tuesday in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most significant segment here is the contactless technology, which allows payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless smart cards were to be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share was expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent over 10% of the global smart card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in contactless payment after being long behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
However, the consumer markets are steaming.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless passport MasterCards this year.
In order to move to a higher speed, it is now necessary for the banks to equip their customers with these cards.
"Two major French financial institutions have committed to systematically handing over to their customers bank cards loaded with contactless chips in the future," said Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
So far, a tiny percentage of devices have been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They're in delay".
"But they should at least experience a real upward trend next year."
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale also announced yesterday that it was preparing to launch an offer that would allow its customers to make contactless payments via mobile phones.
