Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects western Europe directly to Russia, has been put into operation.
It will provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glamour and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, under orchestral sounds on the Baltic coast last Tuesday.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically turned together the control of the valve that transports Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new gas pipeline will deliver 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - is scheduled to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already have the possibility of building a third line on your own route.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building seems like a victory.
The project was heavily controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable direct gas supply to Germany, while avoiding any crossing through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the Hitler-Stalin alliance for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is extremely sensitive from a political point of view.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by endorsing this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of depleting European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has succeeded in enforcing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are experiencing heavy gas consumption and whose gas resources are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers, many of whom are represented in Lubmin, regarding the gas pipeline.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"Around hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precautionary measure," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, that is interrupted over its entire length by nothing: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were little eager to see a Russian state-owned company settle permanently at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be unlikely, as the welding seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation from a seaship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon its arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point and 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company the entire capacity of its gas transport, on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transported gas quantity is," Jens Müller explained.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are willing to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline appears on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give the writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent at candlelight with writing.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic band, the eggshell-coloured sides, as aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as it is known today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, who was a specialist consultant for the company at the time, is tasked with the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton coat used for covering upholstered benches, for example.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now responsible for the brand at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook enthuses businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which in its beginnings had 12 employees, now employs more than 100 people and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookshops, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centers and is committed to asserting its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new writing needs, which persist despite the upswing of emails," explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour (detour)", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a cover with leopard pattern on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and managed to diversify its products: bags, schedules, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the full range of items.
In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today’s Syntegra Capital, and opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled people remain at such a high level?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the 15th week of work for the disabled.
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate of disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% versus 9% of the total population.
- Disheartening?
"No," emphasises Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "Work Week for the Disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high.
"However, there is still a lot to be done."
However, it must be said that there are still many obstacles for disabled people to get a job.
It is more common for the elderly: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with higher education qualifications.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% among the disabled versus 38% on the overall average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to get back into work and that form the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies recruit disabled people.
So much for the factual brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes, which are certain, but still slowly evolving.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge about disabled people" that was "overrepresented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually impaired".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled people, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating back to 2008, point to a 2.6% ratio.
"We are now at around 3%," reports Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization entrusted with collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
Evidence: the number of "fees paying" permanent establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created a strong pressure on the companies," said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real recognition, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of permanent establishments between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled people, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
